Corlear Avenue, west side, north from W. 230th Street.

About 1924

Committee on Housing
Charity Organization Society

West 230th Street (right, not seen), south side, at the foot of Corlear Ave. The driveway, here seen, is the vehicular entrance to the Kingsbridge freight depot of the New York Central Railroad. It runs parallel to West 230th Street, the distance of one block from the foot of Corlear Ave. to the foot of Tibbet Ave. (where automobile house is located). The freight house is at this date (1937) being used by the Mayone Co. of New York, mason suppliers; a new, large and modern freight station having been constructed within the freight yards east of Corlear Ave. The driveway is about 15 feet south of West 230th Street and is separated by a fence.

October 27, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(1)
Corlear Ave., east side, north from West 230th to 231st Streets, showing six 2½-story frame dwellings, the last two of which bear Nos. 3022 and 3026 respectively. Also shown are the rears of the St. John's R.C. Church and the Protestant Episcopal Church of the Mediator, both facing on the west side of Kingsbridge Ave.
October 27, 1927.
